name: Tambohibe
description: The Betsiboka estuary is a highly dynamic forest landscape with seasonal flooding depositing large amounts of silt and soil from inland. Dominated, by mangrove species such as Ceriops tagal, Rhizophora mucronata, and Avicennia marina, the area represents an example of globally important mangrove forest. Mangrove forests are well known for their exceptional value in terms of ecosystem services. Apart of carbon cycling, mangroves also provide significant silt filtration, fish nurseries, and protection against storm surges.

name: Madjuva
description: Madjuva is a critical mangrove habitat that protects Maputo's densely populated capital city. This 190-hectare site will employ and empower the local people to restore and protect their vital ecosystems that have long been overharvested for timber and charcoal. This site features a vast array of flora and fauna that are crucial to the local ecology and the local economy. Fishing and agriculture play a large role in the economy, and through reforestation efforts, Eden hopes to foster sustainable forest management and provide living-wage employment to the native people.
socioeconomic_impacts: Through this project, Eden offers steady employment and income to 42 planters and 12 guards that previously would not have any income. The regular income allows workers to put savings aside, reinvest their income into their household, and start microenterprises to diversify their income opportunities. Also, Eden ensures that each of its workers are registered for federal healthcare giving them access to free medical services through the government. The combination of steady employment and access to federal healthcare serves to restore their self-identity, giving them a voice in the government medical system, and empowering them to seek needed medical care that was previously unavailable.
additional_info_description: Based on careful observation and field studies, Eden's monitoring teams estimate that a minimum of 85% of the trees planted have survived. The planting teams regularly assess the site and carry out replanting as needed to bring the site to full capacity. Also, after the mangroves trees become established, natural regeneration takes over and increases tree numbers by 2 or 3 times the original amount planted.

forest_type.forest_type_species.name: Tectona grandis
forest_type.forest_type_species.description: Tectona grandis (teak) is a tall tree prized for its valuable timber. Teak may grow up to 45 meters (148 ft) tall and 4-5 meters (15 ft) in diameter at maturity (100 years). Occurring naturally in parts of India, Myanmar, Lao PDR, and Thailand, teak has been cultivated in plantations across SE Asia for nearly 400 years. The bark is thin, fibrous, and pale brown or gray. The large, round leaves are shed during the dry season, with new leaves appearing in May-June.

forest_type.forest_type_species.name: Dalbergia sissoo
forest_type.forest_type_species.description: Dalbergia sissoo (Sissoo, Indian Rosewood) is a medium-large deciduous tree growing up to 25 meters (82 ft) tall found primarily along river banks in Nepal's lowland Terai region. Indian Rosewood is known internationally for its timber and valued locally as an essential source of fuelwood, shade, and shelter. This species produces nitrogen-rich fodder and green manures and is used in agroforestry systems to protect and enrich the soil, improve crop production, and diversify farmers' income. The bark is thin, coarse, and gray. The leaves are leathery and pinnately compound.

forest_type.forest_type_species.name: Shorea seminis
forest_type.forest_type_species.description: Shorea seminis (Malaysian sal) is a medium to large-sized hardwood tree that can grow up to 52m (170 ft) tall. Native to Southeast Asia, this species is found in lowland rainforests and along riverbanks. The wood of this species is a high-quality timber used in local construction. The bark has a greenish-brown surface that becomes uneven with an irregular surface when mature. The leaves are alternate and petiolate. The tree does not bear fruit until it is 18-25 years old. The seed produces an edible fat that can be used as a salve to treat skin problems.

forest_type.forest_type_species.name: Acacia catechu
forest_type.forest_type_species.description: Acacia catechu (Khair) is a small to medium-sized deciduous tree growing up to 12-15 meters (45 ft) tall found in tropical forests throughout SE Asia. The bark is rough and dark brown or gray. The wood is valued as timber for construction, while the leaves provide excellent fodder for livestock. Katha (catechu) is an extract of the bark used in tanning, dyeing, and traditional medicine.

name: Antsanitia Dry Deciduous 1
description: The Antsanitia Dry Deciduous site is situated in a unique forest in Madagascar representing dry tropical plant species. The dry deciduous forest is home to many plants and animals that can only be found in this part of the world. Under the threat of clearing due to agriculture, it is being deforested at a rapid rate. This forest must be preserved and reforested to protect the high number of endemic species. Eden has established vital plant nurseries to aid in the reforestation project at this site and has employed a team of native people to carry out this essential mission.

forest_type.forest_type_species.name: Morenga oleifera
forest_type.forest_type_species.description: Morenga oleifera is a drought-resistant tree native to tropical regions around the world. It is commonly known as the benzolive tree since the seeds produce an oil that is used for cooking as well as traditional medicine. Morenfa oleifera can reach heights up to 12 m with a trunk diameter of around 45cm. This tree tolerates a wide range of conditions and is used for alleviating soil erosion.

forest_type.forest_type_species.name: Albizia lebeck
forest_type.forest_type_species.description: Albezia lebbeck, commonly known as the lebbeck tree. This tree can grow 18-30 m tall with a trunk diameter ranging from 50 cm to 1 m. The lebbeck tree produces very fragrant flowers with long seed pods containing six to twelve seeds. There are many economic and environmental resources from the tree including medicinal uses, timber, and foraging.

forest_type.forest_type_species.name: Adansonia
forest_type.forest_type_species.description: Adansonia is a unique deciduous tree endemic to Madagascar. The native people refer to these trees as baobabs which have a reputation around the world for their broad trunks and compact crowns. Baobab tree size often fluctuates with how little or how much rain there is as water is stored in the trunk. The fruit that is produced from baobabs is rich in carbohydrates and often dried to create a powder that is used in ice cream and juices.

forest_type.forest_type_species.name: Artocarpus Heterophyllus
forest_type.forest_type_species.description: Artocarpus Heterophyllus, commonly known as the Jack Tree, is native to tropical regions throughout the world. It can grow 10-20 m tall with a trunk diameter ranging from 30-80 cm. The Jack Tree produces the commonly known jackfruit, which is a large, sweet, aromatic fruit. Jackfruit can be used as a food and has a sweet pineapple-banana-like flavor.

name: Mtwapa Creek
description:
Mangrove forest in Mtwapa Creek has been experiencing significant changes in forest cover
since early 19th Century. The changes in forest cover were accompanied by decline in Mangrove
diversity because of unsustainable harvesting of quality trees. The loss of forest cover has also
been accelerated by gradual growth of population in Mtwapa that rely on forest for firewood,
charcoal and building poles.

forest_type.forest_type_species.name: Avicennia marina
forest_type.forest_type_species.description: Avicennia marina grow as a shrub or tree to a height of three to ten meters, or up to 14 meters in tropical regions. The habit is a gnarled arrangement of multiple branches. It has smooth light-grey bark made up of thin, stiff, brittle flakes.

forest_type.forest_type_species.name: Rhizophora mucronata
forest_type.forest_type_species.description: Rhizophora mucronata is a small to medium size evergreen tree growing to a height of about 20 to 25 meters (66 to 82 ft) on the banks of rivers. On the fringes of the sea 10 or 15 meters (33 or 49 ft) is a more typical height. The tallest trees are closest to the water and shorter trees are further inland. The tree has a large number of aerial stilt roots buttressing the trunk.

forest_type.forest_type_species.name: Ceriops tagal
forest_type.forest_type_species.description: Ceriops tagal is a medium-sized tree growing to a height of 25 meters (80 ft) with a trunk diameter of up to 45 cm (18 in). The growth habit is columnar or multi-stemmed and the tree develops large buttress roots. The radiating anchor roots are sometimes exposed and may loop up in places. The bark is silvery-grey to orangish-brown, smooth with occasional pustular lenticels.

forest_type.forest_type_species.name: Bruguiera gymnorrhiza
forest_type.forest_type_species.description: Bruguiera gymnorrhiza is a small tree up to 10 meters (33 ft) high that belongs to the family Rhizophoraceae. It is found on the seaward side of mangrove swamps, often in the company of Rhizophora. Its bark is rough and reddish brown. The tree develops short prop-roots rather than long stilt-roots.

name: Northern Cheyenne
description: In 2020 and 2021, two large wildfires the Sarpy Fire and Richard Spring Fire advanced across southeastern Montana. The fires burned 232,000 acres of land an area larger than New York city, or 176,000 football fields including parts of the Northern Cheyenne Indian Reservation. The fires blazed through Ponderosa pine forests, which serve as islands of biodiversity in otherwise tree-less plains. Human intervention is now needed to bring these forests back.

name: Santiam State Forest Reforestation
description:
The 2020 Beachie Creek Fire severely burned over 16,000 acres of forest in the Santiam State Forest in Oregon. The fire occurred as part of the larger Labor Day fires that burned over 1 million acres in the state, during a record-breaking drought compounded by climate change and unusually high winds. More than 80% of the Santiam State Forest burned at high severity, limiting the ability of the forest to recover on its own. 

Climate-smart reforestation is needed to jump-start the recovery of the forests and the benefits they provide. Prompt reforestation can begin building back the regions carbon savings account. These forests will also protect cold-water streams for endangered salmon and coastal trout.

name: Williams Lake - 269
description:
This area of Williams Lake, B.C. was devastated by a series of wildfires between 2017 and 2021. Natural regeneration after severe fires can take 40 to 50 years. In some cases, natural forest regrowth isnt possible and the area could be replaced by a bushy shrubland and the original forest would be lost for good. 
 

The restoration of this forest supports local wildlife habitat and Indigenous communities who use the local forest for their traditional hunting range and food sources.

name: Lake Wales Ridge State Forest
description:
This planting project will benefit multiple native wildlife species by improving the structure, composition, and function of the forest. This is in large part achieved by the ability of native pines to establish and sustain a healthy fire regime. Reestablishing longleaf and slash pine at this site will improve wildlife cover, nesting, and browse habitat, and enhance the stands ability to burn in a healthy way by providing more continuous fine fuels. 

The Lake Wales Ridge State Forest plays an integral role in protecting and improving water quality in the Kissimmee Basin, which encompasses more than two dozen lakes in the Kissimmee Chain of Lakes, including their tributary streams and associated marshes, and the Kissimmee River and floodplain.

name: King Fire
description: In mid-September of 2014, an arson fire (the King Fire) ignited in El Dorado County, CA, burning 97,000 acres over the course of a month, including more than 30,000 acres in the Eldorado National Forest where all trees were killed. The severity and extent of the King Fire made it one of the most ecologically damaging fires in this region, where forests evolved in response to low and mixed severity fires typically extending 250 acres or less in size. Without reforestation efforts, much of this burned landscape would become uninterrupted shrub fields that could feed another high intensity fire in the future, with big implications for carbon storage, water cycling, and wildlife habitat. We are planting a mix of incense cedar, sugar pine, ponderosa pine, and Douglas-fir.

name: Forest Gardens
description:
Cotton farming plays an important role in the sub-Saharan African economy and is critical in the fight against rural poverty.

 

Together, we will be supporting local farmers to produce sustainable cotton in a regenerative agroforestry system. The system mixes trees, cotton, and other crops to increase harvest yields while restoring degraded landscapes. Through this project, a diverse range of trees will be planted. This includes avocado, mango, and papaya trees, timber species and animal fodder crops. The goal of this project is to restore the degraded land by integrating planet positive systems. Additional benefits include an improvement in farmers livelihoods and soil quality, increase in cotton yield and restoring native ecosystems for biodiversity to thrive.

name: Klamath National Forest
description: In 2023, 150,000 seedlings will be planted on Californias Klamath National Forest for recovery from the Slater (2020) and McCash Fires (2021). Collectively, the fires burned more than 110,000 acres at high intensity within the Indian Creek and Elk Creek watersheds. Elk Creek is an important water source for nearby communities that have been heavily impacted by the fires. Replanting a mix of native seedlings will help restore the watersheds and revive forest habitat for wildlife, including many species of threatened and endangered species found within the area.
